Below is a **complete, self‑contained example** that shows how you can expose a C++ iterator‑based packet parser (the fictitious `libpcapng` library) to Python with a clean, “Pythonic” API.  
The example uses **pybind11** – the most popular way to write CPython extensions for modern C++.  

The deliverable consists of three files:

| File | Purpose |
|------|---------|
| `pcapng.hpp` | Minimal mock‑up of the real `libpcapng` C++ API (just enough to compile the binding). |
| `pcapng_pybind.cpp` | The actual binding code (the only file you need to compile into a Python extension). |
| `CMakeLists.txt` | A tiny CMake script that builds the extension on any platform that has pybind11 installed. |

After compiling the extension you will get a Python module named **`pcapng`** with the following user‑facing API:

```python
>>> import pcapng
>>> reader = pcapng.PcapReader("capture.pcapng")
>>> # 1️⃣  Use it as a normal Python iterator:
>>> for frame in reader:
>>>     print(frame.timestamp, frame.len, frame.data[:10])
>>> 
>>> # 2️⃣  Or run a user supplied callback on every frame (fast, no Python‑level loop):
>>> def my_handler(frame):
>>>     # frame is a lightweight proxy object; you can read its fields or copy data.
>>>     if frame.len > 1500:
>>>         print("Huge frame at", frame.timestamp)
>>> 
>>> reader.for_each(my_handler)      # <-- GIL is released while iterating.
>>> 
>>> # 3️⃣  Explicit manual iteration (if you need to break early):
>>> it = reader.iter()
>>> while True:
>>>     try:
>>>         frame = next(it)
>>>         if frame.len == 0: break      # stop early
>>>     except StopIteration:
>>>         break
>>> ```
*The iterator is **zero‑copy** – `frame.data` points directly into the native buffer (exposed as a Python `memoryview`).*  

Below you will find the **full source** for the mock library, the binding, and the build script.  The code is heavily commented to explain every design decision.

---  
## 1️⃣  Mock C++ library (`pcapng.hpp`)

> *In practice you would replace this header with the real `libpcapng` headers.  The public API we need to expose consists of*:

* `class Frame` – a plain‑old‑data (POD) structure that holds a timestamp, length, and a pointer to the raw packet bytes.
* `class PcapReader` – opens a file and provides an **input iterator** (`begin()/end()`) that yields `Frame`s.
* `class PcapIterator` – the iterator type that dereferences to a `Frame const&`.

```cpp
// ------------------------------------------------------------
// pcapng.hpp   (mock of the real libpcapng API)
// ------------------------------------------------------------
#pragma once
#include <cstdint>
#include <cstdio>
#include <vector>
#include <string>
#include <stdexcept>
#include <memory>

namespace libpcapng {

struct Frame {
    double timestamp;          // seconds since epoch (double for simplicity)
    uint32_t len;              // length of captured data
    const uint8_t* data;       // pointer into internal buffer (valid until next frame)
};

class PcapReader {
public:
    explicit PcapReader(const std::string& filename) : file_(std::fopen(filename.c_str(), "rb")) {
        if (!file_) throw std::runtime_error("cannot open file: " + filename);
        // In a real implementation we would parse the pcapng header here.
    }
    ~PcapReader() { if (file_) std::fclose(file_); }

    // -----------------------------------------------------------------
    // Input iterator that yields Frame objects.
    // -----------------------------------------------------------------
    class iterator {
        friend class PcapReader;
        PcapReader* parent_ = nullptr;   // non‑owning pointer back to the reader
        Frame current_;                  // the frame we last read (valid until next ++)
        bool at_end_ = false;            // true when we have reached EOF

        // Private ctor used by PcapReader::begin()/end()
        explicit iterator(PcapReader* parent, bool at_end) : parent_(parent), at_end_(at_end) {
            if (!at_end_) ++(*this); // read first frame automatically
        }

    public:
        using iterator_category = std::input_iterator_tag;
        using value_type        = Frame;
        using difference_type   = std::ptrdiff_t;
        using pointer           = const Frame*;
        using reference         = const Frame&;

        iterator() = default;                       // end iterator

        reference operator*() const noexcept { return current_; }
        pointer   operator->() const noexcept { return &current_; }

        // Pre‑increment: read the next frame from the file.
        iterator& operator++() {
            if (at_end_) return *this;
            // ------ Mock reading logic (replace with real parsing) ------
            // Each frame is stored as:
            //   uint64_t timestamp (double)   (8 bytes)
            //   uint32_t length                (4 bytes)
            //   uint8_t  data[length]          (variable)
            // For simplicity we just generate dummy data.
            // ------------------------------------------------------------
            static uint64_t counter = 0;
            if (counter >= 1000) {               // pretend 1000 frames max
                at_end_ = true;
                return *this;
            }
            current_.timestamp = counter * 0.001; // dummy timestamps
            current_.len = 64 + (counter % 64);   // dummy length 64‑127
            // Allocate a static buffer that lives for the whole program.
            static std::vector<uint8_t> static_buf(2000);
            for (uint32_t i = 0; i < current_.len; ++i)
                static_buf[i] = static_cast<uint8_t>((counter + i) & 0xff);
            current_.data = static_buf.data();
            ++counter;
            return *this;
        }

        // Post‑increment (rarely used, but required for a conforming input iterator)
        iterator operator++(int) {
            iterator tmp = *this;
            ++(*this);
            return tmp;
        }

        bool operator==(const iterator& other) const noexcept {
            return (at_end_ && other.at_end_) || (parent_ == other.parent_ && at_end_ == other.at_end_);
        }
        bool operator!=(const iterator& other) const noexcept { return !(*this == other); }
    };

    // -----------------------------------------------------------------
    // Public iterator interface (Python will see this as a normal iterator)
    // -----------------------------------------------------------------
    iterator begin() { return iterator(this, false); }
    iterator end()   { return iterator(this, true);  }

    // -----------------------------------------------------------------
    // Convenience method that accepts a C++ functor and applies it to each frame.
    // The binding will expose this as `PcapReader.for_each(py_callable)`.
    // -----------------------------------------------------------------
    template <typename Callable>
    void for_each(Callable&& fn) {
        for (auto it = begin(); it != end(); ++it) {
            fn(*it);               // `*it` is a `const Frame&`
        }
    }

private:
    std::FILE* file_;   // not used in the mock, but would hold the real file handle
};

} // namespace libpcapng
```

> **What the mock does:**  
> * It pretends that a file contains at most 1000 frames.  
> * Each frame is generated on‑the‑fly with deterministic dummy data.  
> * The iterator is a *real* input iterator (conforms to the C++ standard).  

You can replace the body of `PcapReader::iterator::operator++` with the real parsing code from `libpcapng`.  The rest of the interface stays exactly the same.

